{
  "doc_id": "3002",
  "text": "In order to steer universities towards the market cycle with global competitive needs, increased accountability requirements and growth in managerialism have come to define recent higher education developments in Africa. Consequently new university structures and processes have emerged leading to the growth in the number of administrators. Administrators have acquired more powers and become key players in university governance. This re-engineering of governance has been driven by the belief that in the new globalization, administrators will serve as a linchpin connecting the assets and needs of the campus with the assets and needs of the external environment [CITATION_1] .",
